Task 1: images¶

Read Chapters 27 of Fundamentals of Data Visualizations, then answer the questions below.

Question 1.1¶

What is the difference between vector and bitmap images? Can one always convert between the two?

Answer 1.1¶

A vector image is structured by geometric arrangment of induvidual graphical elements. Each point, x and y coordinate, in a vector image is drawn when the image is rendered. And a bitmap image contain induvidual points (pixels) stored in a grid.

Generally, it is possible to always convert between a vector graphic and a bitmap image. However, when converting a vector graphic into a bitmap format, e.g. a pdf as a png, the key feature of the vecotr graphic (the resolution independence) is lost. And when converting a bitmap image into a vector graphic, the image will still be a bitmap image stored inside a vector gaphic.

Question 1.2¶

What does compression of an image mean? What is the difference between lossless and lossy compression?

Answer 1.2¶

Compression of an image imply the byte minimizing of the graphical file without degrading the image quality to an unaccaptable level, and the file can be decompressed again to the large file.

Lossless compression refers to compression in which the compressed images is pixel-for-pixel identical to the original image. The image is reduced without any quality loss. By lossy compression the image will lose data.

When a lossless compressed image is restored to its original form, no loss of data occurs. On the contrary, when a lossy compressed image is restored to its original form, data is lost.

Question 1.3¶

What is the meaning of color channels? Describe how this is related to how a (raw) bitmap image is stored in memory.

Answer 1.3¶

By combinidig the red, green and blue color channels with different intensities we can get any color we want. Each pixel in a bitmap is represented and stored by these intensities of red, green and blue called RGB color model. If we want a pixel to be black, the pixel is stored as [0, 0, 0].

Task 2: contour plots¶

First learn about contour lines and contour plots at Wikipedia.

Question 2.1¶

What type of data are suitable for visualizing with a contour plot?

Answer 2.1¶

A contour plot helps us visualize a three-dimensional surface on a two-dimensional plane. It is suitable if we want to see how some value Z changes as a function of two inputs, X and Y (Z = f(X,Y)). Example of data that commonly is displayed by a contour plot is cartographic, astrological and meteorological data. Contour lines often visualizes altitude, but can aslo be used to visualize brightness, electrical potential and density.

Task 3: vector fields and quiver plots¶

A vector field is, as it says, mapping which to every point in some domain associates a vector. One can think of it in terms of a fluid in motion: at each point the fluid has a certain velocity. Another way of thinking of a vector field is as the right-hand side in a first order system of ordinary differential equations.

To plot vector fields in two dimensions in Matplotlib one can use the quiver command. First learn about the quiver command, for example by studying this tutorial.

Task 3.1¶

Study the differential equations for the non-linear pendulum). Make a velocity field plot for the pendulum system written as a first order system

$$ \theta' = v, \qquad v' = -\sin\theta. $$

Use the domain $-\pi \leq \theta \leq \pi$ and $-3\leq v \leq 3$. Put $\theta$ on the $x$-axis and $v$ on the $y$-axis.

Modify the plot, adding color to the arrows corresponding to the magnitude of the velocity vectors. Use your own colormap. (Hint: use the C input to the quiver function).

In [ ]:
import matplotlib

# function that calculates the derivate
def f(Y):
    y1, y2 = Y
    return [y2, -np.sin(y1)]


theta = np.arange(-np.pi, np.pi, 0.3)
v = np.arange(-3, 3, 0.3)

T, V = np.meshgrid(theta, v)

t_dir, v_dir = np.zeros(T.shape), np.zeros(V.shape)

I, J = T.shape

for i in range(I):
    for j in range(J):
        x = T[i, j]
        y = V[i, j]
        yprime = f([x, y])
        t_dir[i,j] = yprime[0]
        v_dir[i,j] = yprime[1]

# magnitude of the arrows
mag = np.hypot(t_dir, v_dir)
q = plt.quiver(T, V, t_dir, v_dir, mag, cmap = cubehelix_palette)

plt.xlabel('Angle')
plt.ylabel('Velocity')
plt.xlim([-np.pi, np.pi])
plt.ylim([-3, 3])

Task 4: stream plots¶

Thinking of a vector field as the right hand side of an ordinary differential equation, a stream plot shows one or several curves integrating (solving) this ODE. Each such curve is called a stream line. Start by learning how to use the streamplot function in Matplotlib (find a suitable online tutorial).

Task 4.1¶

Make a streamline plot for the pendulum system in Task 3.1. Use your own color map to indicate velocity. Try to interpret what you see in term of physics of the pendulum motion: Where is the velocity high? Why? What does it mean (in terms of motion of the pendulum) that some curves are circular and some are not? Learn the meaning of the start_points argument to the streamplot function. Use this to generate streamlines that originates from specific points on the positive $y$-axis.

Answer 4.1¶

The velocity is high when $\theta$ is zero, because that is when the velocity of pendelum get as highest (when the pendelum is at the 'bottom', and this is because of the gravity).

Some curves creates circular shapes and some do not. The ones that are circular shows the pendelum motion, that by "swinging" back and forth. The velocity direction points in a positive direction when the pendelum is going one way and it points in a negative direction when the pendelum is going the other way. The curves that are not connected and just points at one direction are visualizing when the velocity is high enough to keep the pendelum going in just one direction (circular).

By the smaller circular curves, that are in the middle of the streamline plot, we can tell that the angle of the pendelum does not get very high and that is because of the low velocity.

# code for streamline plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
start = [[-3, 0], [-3, 2], [-2, 0], [-3, -2], [-0.5, 0], [0, -2.5],  [0, -1], [0, 2.5], [2.8, 2]]
strm = plt.streamplot(T, V, t_dir, v_dir, linewidth=1, color=v_dir, cmap=cubehelix_palette, start_points=start)
fig.colorbar(strm.lines)
plt.title("Streamline plot")

Task 4.2¶

Make a contour plot for the function $f(\theta,v) = v^2/2 - \cos \theta$ for the same domain as in Task 3.1. Compare with the streamline plot for the pendulum system (previous task). What do you observe? Can you explain your observations?

Answer 4.1¶

The two plots look quite similar to each other.

Starting off by understanding the giving function. When the $f$ is equal to or greater than 0, the velocity is low engough to make a pendelum motion (swinging back and forth). And when $f$ is smaller than 0 the velocity is too high to make a pendelum motion.

In the contour plot of this function is described as circular lines when the velocity is low enough to make a pendelum motion and vice versa. For example, when the velocity is smaller than $\sqrt{2}$ and the angle is 0, we can see that there only are circular lines. When the velocity oversteps $\sqrt{2}$ at the angle 0, there are no circular lines.
